%page
%size 6

Protection


	trust process and design over people
	best practices
	documentation
	training
	data validation
	collaboration with third-party providers
	relationship between those who build and administer the systems

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page
%size 6 

Detection


	monitoring, centralized and separate
	baselines and exception reporting
	relationship with upstream providers


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page
%size 6 

Reaction


	incident response plan: NIST templates
		Start with the right stuff. You'll need it later.
	backup communications: XMPP, Signal, PGP
	offline backups
	legal go-to for advice and direction
	again, upstream provider relationship

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

Operational Conclusions


the actual impact in your scenario

	stop thinking security is an absolute
	stop overfocusing on Protection
	there is no product-line that will magically solve security
	Detection and Reaction demands:
		enhancing procedures
		tweaking infrastructure
	start modeling scenarios focused on Detection and Reaction


